Two major classes of filters comprise fibrous and membrane filters. The important filter characteristics are efficiency (capacity to arrest the passage of and hold airborne particles), dust holding capacity, face velocity, and pressure drop. The quality factor (QF) evaluates the filter performance: 2.1QF=ln(1∕P)Δp,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}
$$\displaystyle \begin{aligned} \mathrm{QF} = \dfrac{\ln(1/P)}{\varDelta p}, \end{aligned} $$
\end{document} where P is the penetration and Δp the pressure drop across the filter. The latter increases for a given face velocity when the filter becomes dirty.

